There is strong justification for this due to the impacts of the decision made at the global arena on youth. In Kenya for instance, youth in the 18-35 age bracket constitute about 40 per cent of the population with the number projected to increase.
Kenya can also set a good example as a good global ambassador by turning to President Kenyatta as a focal point in his role as the UN Global Leader for young people.
Appropriate skills
With youth comes energy, innovation, and optimism such that, if a supportive environment and opportunity exists, they can transform the world.
On the other hand, alienated, frustrated, marginalised, and excluded youth, who cannot contribute to any nation’s agenda, is a huge loss to humanity.
Kenya has suffered significantly due to youth-led extremism and violence, which has been categorised as a global challenge. This should bolster our move to facilitate the younger generations with appropriate skills required to excel in the field of international relations.



